  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">STAR 2 - DIALOGUES FOR CHANGE: MPS AND CITIZENS WORKING TOGETHER FOR INCLUSIVE DEVELOPMENT</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A1.1 Project inception meeting/launch with Parliament and Partners and presentation of a paper on the state of Representation in Ghana and how other African parliaments are structured in terms of representation

A1.2 Sensitization forum/dialogue between CSO representatives, media and Parliament on the importance of parliament-citizen engagements as well as develop parliament-citizen engagement guidelines

A1.3 Preparatory activity/training for selected Committees/MPs on Outreach and Citizens engagement
A2.1 Train and sensitise GESI groups and CSO representatives in the Northern Sector on defined parliament-citizen engagement guidelines

A2.2 Train and sensitise GESI groups and CSO representatives in the Southern Sector on defined parliament-citizen engagement guidelines
A3.1 Conduct a baseline survey on parliament-citizen engagement in Ghana to support advocacy actions

A3.2 Organize engagements between target GESI groups and target Committees/MPs in selected districts in the Northern Sector on Health

A3.3 Organize engagements between target GESI groups and target Committees/MPs in selected districts in the Southern Sector on Education</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project seeks to achieve accountability and inclusion in development by bringing citizens&#x2019; voice especially voices of people in hard to reach communities, Unemployed youth, youth in and out of schools, PWDs, uneducated women in the informal sector (small scale business) and CSOs, into the decision-making/law making process in Parliament. As a representative institution, the views expressed by individual Members of Parliament (MPs) and the legislative outcomes of the House as a collective, must be informed by the views, needs and aspirations of the electorate. Although Ghana&#x2019;s presidential democracy has a functioning parliament, institutional representation mechanisms to promote active participation of citizens in the decision-making process remains non-existent. Critical questions bordering on members&#x2019; active representation especially of minority groups such as uneducated poor women, the disabled and young people are usually a subject of contention.</narrative>
  </description>
